<div id="objective-and-contents" class="section level2">
<h2>Objective and Contents :</h2>
<p>The aim of this project is to predict the ‘classe’ variable, of doing the exercice for each partcicpant. The data used is collected from accelerometers on the belt, forearm, arm, and dumbell. In this project we will proceed through the following steps :</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>Preprocessing the data Exploratory data Analysis</li>
<li>Cross validation, training/test split &amp; Exploratory data analysis</li>
<li>Model fitting, Evaluation &amp; model selection</li>
<li>Predictions on the final test set</li>
</ol>
<p>In steps 1 to 3, we will be using only the training data : ‘<a href="https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-training.csv" class="uri">https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-training.csv</a>’.</p>
<p>We will keep the test data : ‘<a href="https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-testing.csv" class="uri">https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-testing.csv</a>’ apart until step 4 (Predictions). Let’s start !</p>
<p>load the data and packages :</p>

<p>Removing the columns with high missing rate :</p>
<pre class="r"><code>maxNA = round(3*nrow(data)/4)   ##-set max NA authorized to be 75% of the data

##-split the data into numeric/character
nmiss = 1:ncol(data)
for( i in 1 : length(nmiss)) {
   nmiss[i]  = length(which(is.na(data[,i]))) + 
      length(which(data[,i] == &quot;&quot;))

}

names_miss = names(data[,which(nmiss &gt;= maxNA)])

complete_data  = data %&gt;% select(-all_of(names_miss))

dim(complete_data)   ####-60 columns with no high missing values</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 19622    60</code></pre>
<p>We can re execute skim(complete_data) and see that there are no missing or empty values in complete_data. there are 56 numeric variables and 4 character one (the ‘classe’ variable + 3 others).</p>
<pre class="r"><code>###-get rid of non interesting variables

nzv_columns = nearZeroVar(complete_data, names = TRUE)


complete_data2 = complete_data %&gt;%
   select(- all_of(nzv_columns) ) %&gt;%  ###-get rid of near zero variance column
   select(-c(&quot;X&quot;))                     ###-get rid of indexes</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="cross-validation-trainingtest-split-exploratory-data-analysis" class="section level2">
<h2>2. Cross validation, training/test split &amp; Exploratory data analysis</h2>
<p>in this section we split our processed training data into new train/test sets. This cross validation will allows us to validate the model before predicting on the final test set:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>set.seed(12354)

index = createDataPartition(y = complete_data2$classe, p=0.75, list = FALSE)

train = complete_data2[index, ] ; test = complete_data2[-index, ]

dim(train) ; dim(test)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 14718    58</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 4904   58</code></pre>
<p>We then proceed to some exploratory data analysis on the training set in order to comprehend our features : charactar features, numeric features, features engineering on train/test sets</p>
<pre class="r"><code>####-character features

round((table(train$classe)/nrow(train))*100)  </code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
##  A  B  C  D  E 
## 28 19 17 16 18</code></pre>
<p>The classe A is 28% percent of the data, the other classes are aound 18%. The data is quite balanced around the outcome variable. The 2 other categorical variables are names and cvtd_timestamp. We won’t be interested to these variables. We will focus on the numerical variables.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>###-check correlation with the classe variable

correlations_data = data.frame(cor(train[,-c(1,4,58)], as.numeric(as.factor(train$classe))) ); colnames(correlations_data) = &quot;correlations&quot;

corr = {correlations_data %&gt;%
  mutate(variables = rownames(correlations_data),
         corr_pos = abs(correlations)) %&gt;%
  arrange(desc(corr_pos)) %&gt;%

corr</code></pre>

<p>The correlations between our class variable and the numeric features are not very high. the highly correlated one (as we can see above) is “pitch_forearm” with only 0.34 correlation. the top 5 correlated features are the only one with correlation above 0.2. let’s visualize the relation between our outcome variable and “pitch_forearm” (the highest correlated feature).</p>
<pre class="r"><code>###we first plot the distribution of the highest correlated feature by classe
###the we plot the second correlated feature vs the third one and color by classe 
suppressMessages(library(gridExtra))

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /> from the two graphs, we can see that only a slight relation can be seen between pitch_forearm and classe (left side multi boxplot) and in the second graph we can’t really detect any pattern by plotting magnet_arm_x vs magnet_belt_y points and color by classe. Thus we will have to use a model in order to understand the relation between “classe” and the features.</p>
<p>But before, let’s check the correlation between our numeric variables</p>
<pre class="r"><code>suppressMessages(library(corrplot))

train_num = train %&gt;% select_if(sapply(train,  is.numeric))%&gt;%
  mutate( &quot;classe&quot; = as.factor(train$classe))

test_num = test %&gt;% select_if(sapply(test,  is.numeric))%&gt;%
  mutate( &quot;classe&quot; = as.factor(test$classe))


corr = cor(train_num[,-56])  ###-correlation matrix of our numeric features

corrplot(corr, method = &quot;circle&quot;, type = &quot;lower&quot; ,  tl.cex = 0.55, tl.col = &#39;black&#39;,  tl.srt = 0.2,
         order = &quot;hclust&quot;
)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>From the correlation plot above, we can see that several ones of our features are highly correlated with each others (the dark red and blue circles). We will use a PCA to reduce our data dimensions (usefull when having a lot of numeric and correlated features).</p>
<div id="pca" class="section level3">
<h3>PCA</h3>
<p>we will create a new training data with the classe outcome and the principal components</p>
<pre class="r"><code>set.seed(123522)

pca = preProcess(train_num[,-56], method = &quot;pca&quot;)

train_pca = predict(pca, newdata = train_num[,-56])
train_pca = train_pca %&gt;%
  mutate(&quot;classe&quot; = as.factor(train_num$classe))

test_pca = predict(pca, newdata = test_num[, - 56])
test_pca = test_pca %&gt;%
  mutate(&quot;classe&quot; = as.factor(test_num$classe))</code></pre>
<p>We have created two new training and test data based on a pca preprocessing. The idea is to use this data to fit, evaluate a model and compare with model fitted on the data before pca processing.</p>
</div>
</div>

suppressMessages(library(&quot;rpart&quot;))

confusionMatrix(pred_tree, test_num$classe)  ###-accuracy on the test set = 84%</code></pre>
